VNC xfce-4

SSH and proxy is already set up on our OS:

1. Downloading the packages

This command will take a while to complete because of the XFCE session packages:

sudo apt-get install tightvncserver xtightvncviewer tightvnc-java xfce4 xfce4-goodies autocutsel -y

2. Configuring the server

Set password for the VNC session by starting the server for the first time:

vncserver

To apply settings for the VNC server you need to create a xstartup file with a config:

sudo nano ~/.vnc/xstartup

Remove current contents contents and then paste:

#!/bin/sh
xrdb $HOME/.Xresources
startxfce4 &
autocutsel -fork

Make the file executable:

sudo chmod +x ~/.vnc/xstartup

3. Starting VNC server on system startup

Create a file containing the configuration of a VNC service that will run on startup:

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/vncserver@.service

And then paste the following content:

[Unit]
Description=Start TightVNC server at startup
After=syslog.target network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=test
Group=test
WorkingDirectory=/home/test
PIDFile=/home/test/.vnc/%H:%i.pid
ExecStartPre=-/usr/bin/vncserver -kill :%i > /dev/null 2>&1
ExecStart=/usr/bin/vncserver -depth 24 -geometry 1920x1080 :%i
ExecStop=/usr/bin/vncserver -kill :%i

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Be sure to change the user and paths according to your config

You'll need to kill the server process that was turned on to create the password:

vncserver -kill :1

This will apply the configuration for the service that was just created:

sudo systemctl daemon-reload

To start the server for testing purposes:

sudo systemctl start vncserver@1

Check if the service is running without any errors:

systemctl status vncserver@1

To make the service run on startup:

sudo systemctl enable vncserver@1

You can then reboot the machine:

5. Bonus tips

The base browser doesn't work for some reason so here is how to get google chrome from CLI:
Wget should work without any need for additional proxy configuration.

wget [https://dl.google.com/linux/direct/google-chrome-stable_current_amd64.deb](https://dl.google.com/linux/direct/google-chrome-stable_current_amd64.deb)
sudo dpkg -i google-chrome-stable_current_amd64.deb

Search for the google chrome app and go into it's properties to set up the proxy configuration:
